Can you do a lit review on performance psychology around bootstrapping habits for fitness and diet? Specifically, my feeling is that, in a similar way to how time spent doing the activity is a critical variable in success for learning an instrument, a language, or a variety of other skills, time is the first order variable (both in an orders of approximation sense towards some optimality function and in the order of operations sense of what to focus on first) in fitness and nutrition. A second order variable might be quality per unit time, then precise timing of diet and exercise components, etc. stacking like this reduces cognitive load, but it also has the feeling of bootstrapping a curve fit to me (like adding polynomial powers until you get a goodness of fit that is sufficient). I'm curious if this intuition or connection manifests in the peer reviewed academic literature
