This is a rich question and the literature actually validates several dimensions of your intuition, though the exact framing of "time as first-order variable" isn't crisply articulated that way in any single paper — you'd be synthesizing across a few adjacent bodies of work. Let me lay it out.

---

## Lit Review: Bootstrapping Habit Complexity in Fitness and Nutrition

### I. The Deliberate Practice Parallel

Your analogy to musical and linguistic skill acquisition has a direct anchor in Ericsson et al.'s (1993) theory of deliberate practice. Ericsson formalized what he called the "monotonic benefits assumption" — the idea that the amount of time invested in domain-specific practice is positively, even monotonically, correlated to the attained performance level. The architecture Ericsson sets up — time on task as the zeroth-order predictor, with quality of that time (feedback structure, targeted weaknesses) as a higher-order modifier — is structurally isomorphic to your framing.

The important nuance the literature developed is that raw time and deliberate practice time are meaningfully different. Ericsson and colleagues distinguished domain-related activities of work, play, and deliberate practice, claiming that accumulated time in deliberate practice specifically is the primary predictor of exceptional performance, though available evidence complicates this claim. The analogy to fitness holds: time in the gym is not the same as time in progressively structured training, but you do need the former before the latter is even accessible psychologically or physiologically.

---

### II. The Asymptotic Curve — Your "Polynomial Fitting" Analogy Has Empirical Form

This is where your intuition finds the clearest direct support. Lally et al. (2010) is the landmark study. Investigating habit formation in everyday life, they followed 96 volunteers performing a chosen eating, drinking, or activity behavior daily in the same context for 12 weeks, and found that automaticity increases follow an asymptotic curve that can be modeled at the individual level. The shape of that curve is exactly what you'd expect from your polynomial analogy: early repetitions yielding larger increases in automaticity than later ones, with a median time of 66 days to reach 95% of the asymptote — varying between 18 and 254 days across individuals.

Critically for your thesis: exercise behaviors took about one and a half times as long to reach their automaticity plateau compared with eating or drinking behaviors, confirming that behavioral complexity modulates the shape and position of the asymptote. This is equivalent to saying that adding polynomial degrees to fit a more complex target function takes longer — the convergence curve is the same shape but with a different time constant.

---

### III. Instigation vs. Execution Habits — A Built-In Hierarchy

The literature has developed a distinction that maps almost exactly onto your "order of operations" framing. Gardner & Lally (2018) distinguish between **instigation habit** (automatically deciding to initiate the behavior) and **execution habit** (automatically performing the sub-actions within it). Current literature suggests that building an instigation habit is more valuable for the maintenance of behavior than an execution habit, since instigation habit involves the direct activation of action and therefore automatically generates behavior performance.

This is your "first-order variable" argument formalized. You need "showing up" to automatize before "how to show up well" can compound on it. For all behaviors studied, habitual instigation predicted behavior frequency, but habitual execution did not — and the habitual instigation process operates identically for simpler and more complex behaviors alike. In other words, the architectural value of getting the first-order variable locked in accrues regardless of what level of execution sophistication you eventually build on top of it.

Kaushal et al. (2017) further subdivided this into **preparatory phase** (all behaviors until exercise-ready state) and **performance phase** (the actual workout), hypothesizing that automating preparation is the more leveraged intervention target — again, your first-order variable argument.

---

### IV. Cognitive Load as the Mechanism — The "Caching" Model

The most mechanistically satisfying account of *why* your ordering strategy works comes from a computational framing. Practice has multiple effects on behavior — increasing speed, rendering behavior habitual, and reducing cognitive load — and these can be explained as consequences of a single principle: caching of frequently occurring computations. The "caching" metaphor is remarkably close to your bootstrapping intuition. This transition is crucial because it frees up higher-order mental resources that can be reallocated for more complex tasks demanding attention — the ability to form habits permits individuals to problem-solve, multi-task, and build simple behaviors into more complex repertoires.

So the sequence has a precise cognitive-resource logic: once the instigation habit is cached (low-order variable automated), the freed executive resources can be deployed toward the next-order variable (intensity optimization, meal timing, periodization). The literature explicitly describes this as enabling hierarchical complexity-building. Once initiation of the action is transferred to external cues, dependence on conscious attention or motivational processes is reduced — therefore habits are likely to persist even after conscious motivation or interest dissipates, and are cognitively efficient because automation of common actions frees cognitive resources.

---

### V. Behavioral Complexity Moderates Automaticity Rate — But Not Its Structure

There's a body of work on how perceived complexity of a behavior affects how quickly it reaches automaticity. Frequency, contextual stability, and rewards each predict high automaticity, with perceived behavioral complexity predicting high automaticity particularly for exercise and medication adherence — more complex behaviors require greater contextual stability to achieve automaticity.

Importantly, for complex behaviors even after habit instigation is established, self-regulation strategy use remains elevated — suggesting that complex behaviors continue to require some deliberate scaffolding even when the instigation is automatic. This is a meaningful qualification on your model: the higher-order variables don't fully "drop out" after bootstrapping; they simply require less active mobilization to bring them to bear. Your curve fit analogy holds — once the lower polynomial terms are fit, they don't disappear from the model; they just stabilize.

---

### VI. The Nutrition Side — Less Developed, But Structurally Similar

The exercise habit literature is substantially deeper than the nutrition habit literature on this point, but the asymptotic dynamics replicate. Modeling habit formation of an everyday nutrition behavior over 12 weeks, Keller et al. (2021) found that of those who successfully formed a habit, a median of 59 days was needed to reach 95% of automaticity, similar to Lally et al., with participants who chose intrinsically rewarding behaviors more likely to show successful habit formation. The key finding relevant to your model is that nutrition habit formation also follows the same asymptotic curve, and also shows that simpler behaviors (e.g., "fruit with lunch") automatize faster than more elaborate ones (e.g., meal-prepping a balanced weekly macro plan).

---

### VII. Where Your Framing Is Novel (and Where the Literature Is Silent)

The lit is clear that: (1) time/frequency is the primary driver of automaticity, (2) automaticity follows an asymptotic curve with diminishing marginal returns per additional repetition, (3) instigation automating before execution is the efficient ordering, and (4) cognitive load reduction through caching is the mechanism enabling hierarchical complexity building.

What the literature **doesn't** do is formalize this as an explicitly sequential, order-of-magnitude hierarchy with a principled stopping criterion analogous to goodness-of-fit. No one has written the version of this that frames it as: "add the next variable when the lower-order variable's contribution to adherence variance has asymptoted." That framing — treating the problem as iterative model-fitting with a parsimony principle — is your contribution. The components are all there in the empirical work; the unifying theoretical lens isn't. If you wanted to write something, that gap is real and the empirical substrate is solid.

_______________________________

There's an interesting correlary to thinking of it this way, which is explaining why sudden bursts of investment fail. A sudden event which motivated a change has two damaging effects, first, it leads to a parity mismatch between cognitive load (perhaps, as measured by number of times in a day the desired activity is thought of) and actual time spend (i.e. someone thinks about exercising 20 times throughout the day but does not do it, which had a sort of dopamine response and effort response with no corresponding action and, therefore, success), and there is an expectation-commitment mismatch such that high effort is expected to yield fast results which are often impossible and commitment is tied to that impossible success, leading to a rebound failure back to baseline. So thinking about bootstrapping as an ideal case within a larger space of sub-optimal function stacking around habit forming is where my head is at. We want to think of the abstract expectation-reward space and the trajectories through it which lead to successful equilibrium states vs those which are inherently unstable. Perhaps I'm trying to make this mathematical mental model stick too closely though. Has this sort of thought process been applied across the areas you discuss or in related fields?

